<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11313&amp;p=130132#p130132"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Any kind of uniform dithering across large plain areas looks weird on the NES when output in NTSC. You always get some sort of pattern, and unless that pattern looks like a plausible texture for the surface in question, it won't look good. I usually try to limit the dithering in my NES pixel work to small and/or noisy areas, so that these phantom patterns aren't so obvious.<br /></div><br />I had problems with all sorts of patterns - except the ones made from horizontal lines.<br />They are artifact-free and according to another topic (<a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=21&amp;t=11018" class="postlink">http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=21&amp;t=11018</a>) they even blend colors on PAL TVs - which is pretty cool.<br /><br />I wish I had an Everdrive to test how tolerable these horizontal lines look on 60 Hz televisions...<br /><img src="http://i5.photobucket.com/albums/y191/macbee/HOMA_zps049eb8c0.jpg" alt="Image" /><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5106">Macbee</a> — Sat Jun 21, 2014 11:07 pm</p><hr />
